Concept Bottleneck Models: Complete Training Walkthrough

An Interactive Tutorial for Interpretable Medical Image Diagnosis

What You'll Learn

In this notebook, you will:

  1. Understand CBM Architecture - Learn how concept bottlenecks enable interpretability
  2. Load & Explore Data - Work with skin cancer diagnosis dataset
  3. Build a CBM from Scratch - Implement the two-stage architecture
  4. Train & Evaluate - Achieve high concept and task accuracy
  5. Concept Intervention - Correct predictions using human expertise
  6. Information Theory - Quantify concept completeness and synergy
  7. Visualize Concepts - See what the model learned

Why Concept Bottleneck Models?

Traditional Black-Box Model 

Image  [Neural Network]  Prediction
         (uninterpretable)

Concept Bottleneck Model 

Image  [Concept Encoder]  Concepts  [Task Predictor]  Prediction
                             ( interpretable + intervention)

Key Advantages:

  • Interpretability: See which concepts drove each prediction
  • Intervention: Correct wrong concepts to fix errors
  • Debugging: Identify when model relies on spurious features
  • Trust: Medical professionals can validate reasoning

Trade-off: ~5% accuracy for full interpretability

2. Load Real Derm7pt Dataset

We'll use the Derm7pt dataset with 7-point checklist concepts for melanoma diagnosis.

Dataset Overview

  • Task: Melanoma vs Non-Melanoma classification (binary)
  • Concepts: 7 clinical attributes, each with 3 classes (Absent/Regular/Irregular)
  • Images: ~1000 dermoscopy images of skin lesions
  • Split: 70% train, 15% validation, 15% test

Concepts (7-point checklist):

  1. Pigment Network
  2. Blue-Whitish Veil
  3. Vascular Structures
  4. Streaks
  5. Pigmentation
  6. Dots & Globules
  7. Regression Structures

# Visualize sample images with concepts
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 3, figsize=(15, 10))
axes = axes.flatten()

# Get a batch
images, concepts, labels = next(iter(train_loader))

class_labels = ['Absent', 'Regular', 'Irregular']
diagnosis_labels = ['Non-Melanoma', 'Melanoma']

for idx in range(6):
    # Denormalize image for display
    img = images[idx].numpy().transpose(1, 2, 0)
    img = img * np.array([0.229, 0.224, 0.225]) + np.array([0.485, 0.456, 0.406])
    img = np.clip(img, 0, 1)
    
    axes[idx].imshow(img)
    axes[idx].axis('off')
    
    # Get diagnosis and concepts
    diagnosis = diagnosis_labels[labels[idx].item()]
    concept_values = concepts[idx].numpy()
    
    # Find present concepts (non-absent)
    present_concepts = []
    for i, val in enumerate(concept_values):
        if val > 0:  # Regular or Irregular
            present_concepts.append(f"{CONCEPT_NAMES[i]} ({class_labels[int(val)]})")
    
    # Title with diagnosis and key concepts
    title = f"{diagnosis}\n"
    if present_concepts:
        title += ", ".join(present_concepts[:2])
    else:
        title += "All concepts absent"
    
    axes[idx].set_title(title, fontsize=9)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Create the CBM model (matching train_basic_cbm.py)
model = ConceptBottleneckModel(
    num_concepts=7,
    num_classes=2,
    num_classes_per_concept=3,  # Absent, Regular, Irregular
    backbone='resnet50',
    pretrained=True
).to(device)

# Count parameters
total_params = sum(p.numel() for p in model.parameters())
trainable_params = sum(p.numel() for p in model.parameters() if p.requires_grad)

print("Model Architecture:")
print("=" * 70)
print(f"Backbone:          ResNet50 (pretrained on ImageNet)")
print(f"Concept Encoder:   7 concepts  3 classes = 21 outputs")
print(f"Task Predictor:    Linear layer (21  2)")
print("=" * 70)
print(f"Total parameters:     {total_params:,}")
print(f"Trainable parameters: {trainable_params:,}")
print("=" * 70)

# Test forward pass
with torch.no_grad():
    test_images = torch.randn(2, 3, 224, 224).to(device)
    test_concepts, test_logits = model(test_images)
    
print(f"\n Forward pass successful!")
print(f"\nOutput shapes:")
print(f"  Concepts: {test_concepts.shape}  (batch=2, conceptsclasses=73=21)")
print(f"  Logits:   {test_logits.shape}  (batch=2, num_classes=2)")
print(f"\nConcept output interpretation:")
print(f"  - Shape [2, 21] represents [batch, 7 concepts  3 classes]")
print(f"  - Reshape to [2, 7, 3] to get probabilities per concept")
print(f"  - Argmax over last dim gives predicted class per concept")

4. Train the Model

Now let's train the CBM model using the joint training strategy.

In[6]:
# Training configuration (matching train_basic_cbm.py)
NUM_EPOCHS = 50
LEARNING_RATE = 1e-4
PATIENCE = 25
OUTPUT_DIR = '../outputs/notebook_cbm'

# Create output directory if it doesn't exist
import os
os.makedirs(OUTPUT_DIR, exist_ok=True)

# Initialize trainer
from src.training.trainer import CBMTrainer

trainer = CBMTrainer(
    model=model,
    train_loader=train_loader,
    val_loader=val_loader,
    learning_rate=LEARNING_RATE,
    training_strategy='joint',
    device=device
)

print(f"\nTraining CBM model for {NUM_EPOCHS} epochs...")
print(f"Strategy: joint")
print(f"Learning Rate: {LEARNING_RATE}")
print(f"Early Stopping Patience: {PATIENCE}")
print(f"Output Directory: {OUTPUT_DIR}")
print("=" * 50)
print("\nTraining in progress (output suppressed)...")

# Train the model with suppressed output
import sys
from io import StringIO

# Capture stdout to suppress verbose training output
old_stdout = sys.stdout
sys.stdout = StringIO()

try:
    history = trainer.train(
        n_epochs=NUM_EPOCHS,
        save_dir=OUTPUT_DIR,
        early_stopping_patience=PATIENCE
    )
finally:
    sys.stdout = old_stdout

print("\n" + "=" * 50)
print("Training Complete!")
print(f"Best Validation F1: {trainer.best_val_acc:.4f}")
print(f"Model saved to: {OUTPUT_DIR}")

7. Concept Intervention - The Magic of CBMs!

This is where CBMs shine: we can intervene on concept predictions to fix errors.

Scenario: Model predicts wrong concepts wrong diagnosis
Solution: Correct the concepts to ground truth prediction may improve!

Let's find a test case and demonstrate intervention.

In[10]:
# Find a test case to demonstrate intervention
best_model.eval()

# Get test samples
test_images_batch, test_concepts_batch, test_labels_batch = next(iter(test_loader))
test_images_batch = test_images_batch.to(device)

# Run predictions
with torch.no_grad():
    pred_concepts, pred_logits = best_model(test_images_batch)
    pred_classes = pred_logits.argmax(dim=1)

# Select first sample
sample_idx = 0
original_image = test_images_batch[sample_idx:sample_idx+1]
original_concepts_flat = pred_concepts[sample_idx]  # Shape: [21]
original_logit = pred_logits[sample_idx]
true_concepts = test_concepts_batch[sample_idx]  # Shape: [7] (ground truth class per concept)
true_label = test_labels_batch[sample_idx].item()

# Reshape concepts for interpretation: [21]  [7, 3]
original_concepts_reshaped = original_concepts_flat.reshape(7, 3)
pred_concept_classes = original_concepts_reshaped.argmax(dim=1).cpu().numpy()

diagnosis_labels = ['Non-Melanoma', 'Melanoma']
class_labels = ['Absent', 'Regular', 'Irregular']

print("Original Prediction (without intervention):")
print("=" * 70)
print(f"True Label: {diagnosis_labels[true_label]}")
print(f"Predicted:  {diagnosis_labels[pred_classes[sample_idx].item()]}")
print(f"Confidence: {torch.softmax(original_logit, dim=0).max():.2%}\n")

print("Concept Predictions vs Ground Truth:")
print("-" * 70)
for i, concept_name in enumerate(CONCEPT_NAMES):
    pred_class = int(pred_concept_classes[i])
    true_class = int(true_concepts[i].item())
    match = "" if pred_class == true_class else ""
    print(f"{match} {concept_name:25s} Pred: {class_labels[pred_class]:10s}  GT: {class_labels[true_class]:10s}")

# Intervention: Set concepts to ground truth
print("\n" + "=" * 70)
print("INTERVENTION: Correcting concepts to ground truth")
print("=" * 70)

# Create one-hot encoded concepts from ground truth
intervened_concepts = torch.zeros(1, 7, 3, device=device)
for i in range(7):
    gt_class = int(true_concepts[i].item())
    intervened_concepts[0, i, gt_class] = 1.0

# Flatten to [1, 21] for model input
intervened_concepts_flat = intervened_concepts.reshape(1, -1)

with torch.no_grad():
    intervened_logits = best_model.task_predictor(intervened_concepts_flat)
    intervened_pred = intervened_logits.argmax(dim=1).item()
    intervened_prob = torch.softmax(intervened_logits[0], dim=0)

print(f"\nAfter Intervention:")
print(f"  Predicted: {diagnosis_labels[intervened_pred]}")
print(f"  Confidence: {intervened_prob.max():.2%}")
print(f"\nResult: {' Correct!' if intervened_pred == true_label else ' Still incorrect'}")

# Show probability change
orig_prob = torch.softmax(original_logit, dim=0)
print(f"\nProbability shift:")
print(f"  Melanoma: {orig_prob[1]:.2%}  {intervened_prob[1]:.2%} ({intervened_prob[1] - orig_prob[1]:+.2%})")
print(f"  Non-Melanoma: {orig_prob[0]:.2%}  {intervened_prob[0]:.2%} ({intervened_prob[0] - orig_prob[0]:+.2%})")

8. Inspect Learned Concept Weights

Since we used a linear task predictor, we can directly inspect which concepts contribute to melanoma diagnosis!

In[12]:
# Get learned weights from linear task predictor
# Shape: [num_classes=2, num_concept_logits=21]
weights = best_model.task_predictor.predictor.weight.detach().cpu().numpy()

print("Task Predictor Weights Shape:", weights.shape)
print("  (num_classes=2, num_concept_logits=73=21)")

# For each concept, sum the absolute weights across its 3 classes
concept_importances = []
for concept_idx in range(7):
    # Get weights for this concept's 3 classes
    start_idx = concept_idx * 3
    end_idx = start_idx + 3
    
    # Sum absolute values of melanoma class weights for these 3 classes
    melanoma_weight = np.abs(weights[1, start_idx:end_idx]).sum()
    concept_importances.append(melanoma_weight)

concept_importances = np.array(concept_importances)

# Visualize
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(16, 6))

# Bar plot of concept importance
concept_names_display = CONCEPT_NAMES
colors = plt.cm.viridis(np.linspace(0, 1, 7))

ax1.barh(range(len(CONCEPT_NAMES)), concept_importances, color=colors, alpha=0.7, edgecolor='black')
ax1.set_yticks(range(len(CONCEPT_NAMES)))
ax1.set_yticklabels(concept_names_display)
ax1.set_xlabel('Total Absolute Weight (3 classes)', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
ax1.set_title('Concept Importance for Melanoma Prediction', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
ax1.grid(axis='x', alpha=0.3)

# Sorted by importance
sorted_idx = np.argsort(concept_importances)[::-1]

ax2.bar(range(len(CONCEPT_NAMES)), concept_importances[sorted_idx], 
        color=colors[sorted_idx], alpha=0.7, edgecolor='black')
ax2.set_xticks(range(len(CONCEPT_NAMES)))
ax2.set_xticklabels([concept_names_display[i] for i in sorted_idx], rotation=45, ha='right')
ax2.set_ylabel('Total Absolute Weight', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
ax2.set_title('Concept Ranking (Most Important First)', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
ax2.grid(axis='y', alpha=0.3)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Print interpretation
print("\n" + "=" * 70)
print("Concept Importance Analysis:")
print("=" * 70)
print("\nRanked by total influence on melanoma prediction:\n")

for rank, idx in enumerate(sorted_idx, 1):
    importance = concept_importances[idx]
    print(f"  {rank}. {concept_names_display[idx]:25s} {importance:.3f}")

print("\n" + "=" * 70)
print("Interpretation:")
print("=" * 70)
print("Higher values = More influence on final diagnosis")
print("These weights show how much the model relies on each concept")
print("for making its melanoma vs non-melanoma decision.")

Model Performance:

  • Concept Accuracy: ~85-90% (model learns clinically meaningful features)
  • Task Accuracy: ~80-85% (competitive with black-box models)
  • Task F1 Score: ~0.75-0.85 (good balance of precision/recall)

Interpretability Trade-off:

  • CBMs achieve similar performance to black-box models
  • Gain: Full interpretability + intervention capability
  • Cost: Slightly more complex architecture

Insights

What the Model Learned:

  • Most important concepts typically: Blue-Whitish Veil, Atypical Pigment Network, Irregular Pigmentation
  • Matches clinical knowledge from dermatology!
  • Linear predictor shows direct contribution of each concept

Intervention Power:

  • Correcting wrong concepts can flip incorrect predictions
  • Enables human-AI collaboration
  • Clinicians can override model when they disagree
